    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Deep Dive — How Step 5 Works and Why It Succeeds\"\nformat:\n  html:\n    toc: true\n    toc-depth: 3\n---\n\n\n\n## Part 1 — DBSCAN-Built Thresholds (ThresholdV2)\n\n### Why the old thresholds (V1) were not enough\n\nSteps 1–4 rely on hand-crafted or statistically naive min/max price ranges.  A single\nextreme purchase can widen a V1 threshold so much that it matches too broadly — or, when\ndata is sparse, the range is too tight to match realistic new transactions.\n\n### What DBSCAN does differently\n\n**DBSCAN** (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) groups historical\npurchase prices for each product into *dense clusters* while treating statistical outliers\nas noise.  The resulting ThresholdV2 records store:\n\n- `MinThreshold` / `MaxThreshold` — the actual observed price range of the cluster (not a\n  hand-tuned rule).\n- `QuantityOfEAInUOM` — the UOM quantity that cluster represents.\n- `MeanEA` — a per-each price anchor used when no WAP entry is available.\n\nBecause outliers are excluded, the clusters are tighter and more representative of real\nanalyst expectations.  A product that historically sells as a **BX/12** at $120–$180 will\nproduce one cluster with that range; a separate cluster covers the **EA** sales at $10–$15.\n\n---\n\n## Part 2 — The Proximity Inference Formula\n\nOnce DBSCAN clusters exist, Step 5 must decide which cluster (UOM) best explains the\ncurrent line's `PriceUOM`.  The key insight is that price operates on a **log scale** —\na $5 difference matters much more at a $10 product than at a $10,000 product.\n\n### Log-distance calculation\n\n```\nlogPrice = log₁₀(max(PriceUOM, 0.0001))\nlogLo    = log₁₀(max(MinThreshold, 0.0001))\nlogHi    = log₁₀(max(MaxThreshold, 0.0001))\n\nlogDist  = 0                        if  lo ≤ price ≤ hi\n         = logPrice − logHi         if  price > hi   (above range)\n         = logLo − logPrice         if  price < lo   (below range)\n```\n\nIf the price falls *inside* the cluster band, the log-distance is exactly 0 — a perfect\nmatch.  Outside the band the distance grows as the log ratio between the price and the\nnearest edge.\n\n### Gaussian proximity score\n\n```\nproximityScore = exp(−0.5 × (logDist / LOG_EPS)²)    where LOG_EPS = 0.25\n```\n\nThis is a **Gaussian kernel on log-price space**.  `LOG_EPS = 0.25` corresponds to roughly\na 1.8× price deviation from the cluster edge before the score drops to ~0.37.  At a 2×\ndeviation the score is ~0.02 — effectively zero.\n\n**Why this mirrors analyst reasoning:**\n\nAnalysts verify a UOM assignment by mentally checking whether the price is \"in the right\nballpark\" for that product and pack size.  A box of 10 syringes should cost roughly 10×\nwhat one syringe costs.  If the file price is 3× or 20× off, the analyst rejects it.\nThe proximity score formalises this intuition: prices within the cluster score near 1.0,\nprices slightly outside drop gracefully, and wildly mismatched prices score near 0.\n\n### Four candidate pools\n\nStep 5 evaluates up to four candidate sources and picks the one with the highest proximity\nscore:\n\n| Source | What it is | Why it's included |\n|--------|-----------|-------------------|\n| **DBSCAN** | Cluster from ThresholdV2 | Primary signal — density-derived from history |\n| **Known Product UOM** | WAP (Weighted Avg Price) from purchase history | Covers UOMs not yet in DBSCAN clusters |\n| **EA/1 WAP** | Per-each derived from any known WAP ÷ quantity | Catches single-unit sales missing from DBSCAN |\n| **File UOM × WAP** | File-stated UOM quantity × per-each WAP | Validates when the supplier already labelled the pack size |\n\nThe File UOM candidate requires a minimum score of **0.85** to be considered — a stricter\nbar because file labels are not always reliable.\n\n---\n\n## Winner-Source Breakdown\n\n::: {#38dffe15 .cell execution_count=2}\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div>            <script src=\