\\,400 | 58\\.4 % |\n| Some history (≥ 5 units) | 21\\,900 | 40\\.7 % |\n\n: {.striped .hover}\n\n- **Zero history** — DBSCAN cannot form a cluster without past transactions.  No ThresholdV2\n  exists, and no WAP can be derived.  Step 5 has nothing to anchor its proximity calculation\n  against.\n- **Very low history (1–4 units)** — a single purchase creates a technically valid cluster,\n  but with such sparse data the cluster edges may be wildly unrepresentative.  The proximity\n  score lands below the 0.30 acceptance threshold.\n- **Some history but low confidence** — the product has enough data for DBSCAN, but the\n  file's `PriceUOM` is far enough from every cluster that no candidate scores ≥ 0.30.\n  This typically means the supplier is quoting an unusual pack size not yet seen in history,\n  or there is a unit-price vs pack-price mismatch in the file.\n\n### 3. PriceUOM not present in purchase history\n\nSome rows have a `PriceUOM` value but that price point has never appeared in the product's\npurchase history.  With no matching cluster and no comparable WAP anchor, the inference\nstep cannot form a confident assignment — the proximity score for every candidate falls\nbelow 0.30 and the row exits unrecognized.\n\n---\n\n*See **Proposed Solutions** for how these three failure modes can be addressed.*\n\n",
